Variation. Dorsal coloration is highly variable, with nearly 25 % of the examined specimens presenting a light, thin vertebral stripe, from the tip of the snout to vent. In preserved specimens, the gular region may vary from light to darker grey, always peppered with black melanophores. Females have a more robust body and their gular region, although areolate, is always unpigmented, clear white (
Table 1
